atically discusses the various structures of Latin hexameter - enjambement, synaloepha, hiatus, four-word lines, name-lines, relevant juxtapositions etc. - in terms of "effects", showing how they interact and converge in the text. This introduction to Virgil's expressiveness aims to be an effective tool for a stylistic reading of any Latin hexametric text.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2019) 0aLatin languagexWord order. 4aAeneid. 4aAeneis. 4aAusdruckskraft. 4aHexameter. 4aOrdo verborum. 4aexpressiveness. 4ahexameter. 4aword order. 70(DE-601)1041938590(DE-588)4293329-8aExpressivitätgLinguistik2gnd 70(DE-601)1056664400(DE-588)4135250-6aWortstellung2gnd 70(DE-601)1056873910(DE-588)4132483-3aSprachstil2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aCampbell, Ailsa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2015z9783110438604oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97831104011270 cprintz978311038422240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110401028423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110401028.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aZDB-23-DGDb2015  aZDB-23-DGGb2015